      "id": "d3397f83557eccc7",
      "text": "The three elements of the syndrome of total violence not only coincide, they mutually exalt each other."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "16d304a31602fa32",
      "text": "Glorification and indifference promote each other mutually: glorifications of one's own act of violence become even more unobjectionable, even more undisturbed possible, if the opponent is a nothing – albeit a dangerous nothing – whose counter-motives cannot even enter into a [[Comparison]]. Conversely, the more one's own ideals and heroic deeds outshine the entire conflict, the more indifferent the other becomes to the killer."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "553206b71c1c925b",
      "text": "Similarly, glorification and indifference facilitate the willingness to use technical means of violence, and the mechanization of violence has an effect on both attitudes. Missiles, satellites, radar, electronics, lasers, supersonic bombers – all this magnificent accumulation of speed, maneuverability, precision, power, dynamism makes humans partakers and controllers of such speed and power. Through technology, people who master it become fabulously potent. The glory of technology fits perfectly to the glory of violence. And so the technical perfection fits to the unaffectedness of the perpetrator. It is different to strangle a man with bare hands than to hit him with an arrow. The arrows gain greater and greater ranges, some button or lever takes the place of the cocked bow. The connection of one's own action with the consequences becomes more invisible, more unintelligible. What is needed is objective concentration, emotions can only disturb."
