        "text": "The trains of thought I have followed so far are rather confirmed by this permanent self-exaggeration of man's power to injure. In any case, they are not suitable for reassurance before the threatening dangers. But they should be suitable for the question which counterforces are conceivable. Admittedly, we will not find the move that saves the draw. On the contrary, whoever asks the question about counterforces must be prepared for considerations that sound illusory.\n\nOf course, any arms limitation and any disarmament is  useful. But to stop the progression of total violence with some reliability and permanence, it is necessary not only to limit the number of weapons, but also to refrain from developing new ones. If this is not done, any agreement will be overrun in a short time by innovations that were not negotiated. To refrain from developing new weapons is either to block the translation of research into technical applications or to prevent research in the field of weapons technology altogether. Both run into infinite difficulties of detail. In general, both would be an attempt to exclude in principle man's fundamental capacity for technical manufacturing, his manufacturing intelligence, from a wide field.\nIs even the will for such an attempt conceivable? Probably only in the sign of a great fright and in the sign of the realization that the continuation of the arms competition increases the security of neither side, but increasingly reduces it. This could lead to the realization that our traditional military-strategic understanding of security no longer makes sense in the face of nuclear confrontation. The security that must be sought in this situation can only be a security of both sides.\n\nA coordination of conflict strategies in which the security of both sides is taken into account and promoted -\" presupposes, as experience shows, a minimum of trust. Thus, it cannot be sufficient merely to bring the technical element of the syndrome of total violence under control. Even a minimum of confidence is unthinkable if the possibility of a nuclear\n\n"
